Sure, here are some example sentences that use the word "laka" in different forms and positions:

1. *Laka* je biljka za uzgoj. (Easy is a plant to grow.) 
2. Kako možemo učiniti ovaj zadatak *lakšim*? (How can we make this task easier?)
3. Njegov *laki* smijeh nas je opustio. (His light laughter relaxed us.)
4. Ona je *laka* na riječima, ali teško da će ostvariti svoje obećanje. (She is easy with her words, but unlikely to keep her promise.)
5. *Lako* je reći, ali teško učiniti. (It's easy to say, but hard to do.)
6. Želim *laku* torbu koju mogu nositi svaki dan. (I want an easy bag that I can carry every day.)
7. *Lakoća* njegovog pokreta privukla je pažnju publike. (The ease of his movement drew the attention of the audience.)
8. *Lakomislenost* je dovela do njegovog neuspjeha. (His recklessness led to his failure.)

Note: In Serbian, the word "laka" can have different forms depending on the grammatical case, gender, and number. In the examples above, I used the nominative singular masculine form "laka" in sentences 1, 3, 4, and 6; the comparative adjective "lakšim" in sentence 2; the adverb "lako" in sentence 5; the nominative singular feminine form "laka" in sentence 6; the noun "lakoća" in sentence 7; and the noun "lakomislenost" in sentence 8.